so i had therapy today with my old therapist, who is now my current therapist again. Yay. seriously, Yay. After therapy, I had a few hours to spend before i could go work on projects in the arts and journalism building, so I went for a drive along the white river, while the sun was setting. It was beautiful, orange and blue and red, it was amazing. So for some reason, i went out to where i used to work, just to drive by the house. Very melancoly. So i talked to myself, all about what i want to say to the teacher tomorrow. Still struggling with what to say, but from talking with t it is apparent i need to say something. *sigh* 

but i am feeling okay today... lots to do before the end of the week, but okay. I have been given a great gift, and I am not going to allow anything to stand in my way of becoming who i can be.

I am in the middle of a Cat War, as the members of my household adjust to life with the new member, Vincent. Ginger, the chihuahua, likes to play and chase the kitten, but gets upset that Vincent plays with her toys. The Cats, well, Lucy is the only cat to inhabit the livingroom (where the kitten spends most of his time). She growls when he comes near, but she gets attention from me (she is on my lap right now). Maria and Phoebe are hiding in the bathroom, Maria hiding IN THE CABINETS. The kitten is that horrible to her, THE CABINETS. lol. The only thing I worry about the kitten is that Ginger is harrassing it too much. Ginger loves to play, and the kitten loves to play, so they are having a good time, but I think Vincent gets a little overwhelmed. He will sometimes just start crying, and I go look for him, and Ginger has him cornered somewhere, tapping her paws in front of him, trying to get him to play.
My new kitten, Vincent

a narrative of the past few day's events, with pictures We went from Tampa down to Pine Island, stopping at a nice beach along the way... I picked up shells and generally enjoyed myself. We didnt stay long, because we wanted to get to Aunt Gerrie's at a reasonable time. We visited with her for a whole day, eating dinner at Captain's Cove, a local seafood shack on the beach. I had the best damn fried clams I've ever had. I heard a lot of family gossip, painted a bit, and generally tried to pass the time without being a nuisance to my mom. yesterday we stopped at two manatee parks, and enjoyed them both very much. It is so peaceful to stand and watch them slowly moving in the water. We stopped at a janky trucker motel 20 miles from orlando, cheapest hotel we had. We ate dinner at a bar attached to the motel, crappy pizza. I played pool and drank a Schmirnoff Ice, and had an okay time. Today we went to Seaworld. Mom didnt enjoy Seaworld as much as I did, she was spoiled by Busch Gardens. It was more crowded, and there wasnt a trolley system to get from one area to the other, so there was a lot of walking. mom was having trouble with her hips, and we had to stop frequently. I didnt mind, i just wish she would take a break before getting grouchy. We stopped at the stingray petting area and I took full advantage of petting them. They are slimy, and rough at the same time. They like to be pet, they will see your hand and swim up to it, and leisurly swim past. I had one that kept swimming back to me to get pet over and over. We then made our way to the dolphin pool, where I spent some cash and fed the dolphins. I really enjoyed the dolphins, they know exactly how many fish you have, and will swim away when you run out. The trainer would signal some to come over if they notice you had been left out. We saw captive manatee, and got a closer look. These manatee had a lighter skin tone, and were much fatter than wild manatee. One had been seriously injured by a boat, she was missing half her tail and part of one flipper. We then went to the dolphin show, which was extremely hoaky, but i have a few pics: We ate lunch, then went to the Shamu Show. It was impressive! The arctic adventure was okay, the polar bears were indoors and they looked so depressed. The walrus was feeling good, and I think he was actually pleasing himself in front of all the guests. He kept floating up and down and rubbing his, um, belly area. I now have a huge thing for beluga whales... absolutely love them aaand of course i have some pictures: We couldnt see the otters between shows, which was dissappointing. Mom was getting tired so I suggested we go back to the dolphin area where I could feed dolphins again and she could sit at the smoking area and rest. I spent another hour with the dolphins, loving every minute. I tried to take some pictures of myself with them and they failed, but a brittish lady was nearby and offered to take what has become my favorite picture of the whole trip. Then i made mom come down and take some more pics of me with the dolphins. Well, the park was closing and I wanted one more picture to remember this awesome day. So now we are at the hotel. We ate at this awesome biker restaurant/bar, well, more for touristy bikers. I had the best shrimp ever, bigger than your thumb and tasty! We are only fooling ourselves when eating seafood in indiana. Tomorrow we are going to stop at the beach again so I can see the atlantic ocean before heading towards the smokies.

Well today was just wonderful. We found Busch Gardens with little difficulty, got a great parking space and were there just as the park opened. The park wasnt busy, there were around 5000 people there and they said a busy day would have around 35000. This was great because the lines werent long, and there werent people crowding around you to look at things. The animal exhibits here are AMAZING. I'm gonna post pictures next, to keep them under a cut. I rode one coaster, but didnt brave Sheikra, with the 90 degree drop... im a chicken without friends around to egg me on to do stupid things. All I could think looking at it was about when we were at Cedar Point and Val kept saying "what have we done" or something like that as we were going up the hill on Mantis... You get so close to the animals, its unreal. My favorite were the tigers, as they were play fighting as we watched... see the pics. The food was great, they actually included healthy choices for people who dont want to eat junk. We saw the show "Katonga" which is a lion king on broadway rip off, but it was really well done and fun. The little kid next to me started crying because there is a part with lightning and it was a little intense. I took tons of photos, and it was hard to choose which ones to share. We ended the day riding the gondalas across the park, getting a birds eye view of the animals. We are going to drive down along the coast tomorrow towards Aunt Gerrie's house. I'll be offline for a few days, cuz i think we are staying with her. 

peace out y'all

Woohoo for day three! We are in Tampa Bay, staying in a comfort inn along 75. Tomorrow is Busch Gardens. Today we went to MOSI, the Museum of Science and Industry, on a whim. There was a sign on the interstate advertising "Bodies the Exhibition", which appeared to be an exhibit that I had seen on TV and wanted to see in person... unfortunately it wasnt exactly the same exhibit, but similar. I think the one I want to see is called "Body Worlds"... So then we went over to the Salvador Dali Museum, which was awesome. Just amazing, i am really inspired to paint tonight... and i cant wait till i can afford oil paints. We stopped and ate dinner then went over to a Manatee park, but it was closed, then there was another park but it was closed as well. At 6pm! So here we are in the hotel room, sitting around. I am going to paint, then read the book i bought at a Dollar store in Tifton Georgia about an alien that is stranded in Midevil Europe... it sounds stupid but it is actually a fun read

Teen With Peanut Allergy Dies After Kiss
Email this Story

Nov 28, 11:54 AM (ET)

SAGUENAY, Quebec (AP) - A 15-year-old girl with a peanut allergy died after kissing her boyfriend, who had just eaten a peanut butter snack, hospital officials said Monday.

Christina Desforges died in a Quebec hospital Wednesday after doctors were unable to treat her allergic reaction to the kiss the previous weekend.

Desforges, who lived in Saguenay, about 155 miles north of Quebec City, was almost immediately given a shot of adrenaline, a standard tool for treating the anaphylactic shock brought on by a peanut allergy, officials said.

An autopsy was being performed. Dr. Nina Verreault, an allergist at the Chicoutimi Hospital in Saguenay, declined to comment on the case.

The symptoms of peanut allergy can include hives, plunging blood pressure and swelling of the face and throat, which can block breathing.

Peanut allergies have been rising in recent decades. The reason remains unclear but one study found that baby creams or lotions with peanut oil may cause children to develop allergies later in life.

About 1.5 million Americans are severely allergic to even the smallest trace of peanuts and peanut allergies account for 50 to 100 deaths in the United States each year. Canadian figures were not immediately available.

im not sure what to think about today. i went to my mom's because the insurance adjuster was sposed to call, but he never did. the girls were there, the whole freakin time, screaming and yelling and manhandling ginger all day. then mom and i went to see a movie, which was pretty good (Elizabethtown), even better because we  have friends in E-town and the movie really hit the nail on the head. 

i'm afraid of going full-tilt nuts. I'm watching a movie right now, called My Sister's Keeper, on the Halmark channel. Kathy Bates is the crazy sister of some chick who works in an art gallery. I just... i see the Kathy Bates character as a future version of me. I just... i dont want to be a burden on my family, and I am headed down that road. i have these ideas for being a painter, but what if it's all just pipe dreams... what if my future is full of hospitalizations and medications and therapy and that;s it? The mother dies and Kathy says she just wanted her mom to be proud of her, and she thought she never was... i want a life my mother will be proud of, and living holed up in a trailer working shit jobs isnt it. urges are bad tonight, have been all day. just, just feeling very fragile and the girls were on my last nerve. 

kathy bate's character at one point says "You know the meds are just covering up the real me" or something like that... and it's so true. the real me, whoever that is, will never see the light of day so long as i medicate. but the alternative?

nightmare again... this time i was staying in the dorms at some generic school, and i was weeding plants. my hands started to hurt and itch, and when i looked at them, i had plants growing all over my palms. i pulled them out, then went to the sink to wash them, and then i had leeches sticking in my skin on my hands. as i pulled them out, they turned into maggots, which i started pulling out. there was a maggot in my armpit, and i pulled and pulled and it just got longer, then finally i got it off. then i woke up. 

on a good note, mom and i went shopping for art supplies, and i have discovered the joy of Arches 140 lb cold press... it is the shit, best paper ive ever used. i also got a presentation book to display my stuff... art shit is so expensive. i payed 9.60 per sheet of paper... then looked online and dick blick has it for less than 4.00, so i'll be ordering mine online from now on...

k, so I'm sitting at home in Indiana, and the one thing i really want to do is go down to the areas hit by Katrina, or the shelters in various cities, and help out. I know, I wouldnt be much help to anyone and just another mouth to feed, but I just wish there was more I could do besides send money to the Red Cross. I cant believe people are just dying in the streets, little babies going without food and water. Grandma's dying and being left on the side of the road. I also cant believe how callous some people are being, I was listening to the radio and this guy was basically saying everyone who stayed asked for it and deserved what they got. Well, tell me what you'd do if you were dirt poor and didnt have a car or anywhere to go. If your job meant you stayed at the hospital with patients. You're 90 and cant walk and your family doesnt stay in touch. I'm not supporting the mass chaos, the idiots out there with guns shooting at people trying to help, so far as I am concerned lethal force if necessary to rid the area of assholes doing that sort of thing. But how can you look at the mothers with young children and not want to get them out of there? How can you not want to get formula to those kids? And I just wonder what is going on with the MR/DD population of the coast. Did the group homes and ICF/MRDD facilities evacuate in time? Where have they gone and how long can they stay there? What are we as a nation doing to get them help? Does anyone care? I just wish there was more I could do. I wish i had a truck i could load up with supplies and just take off work and drive down. Aside from not having a truck, the main thing keeping me here is the knowledge that my job is short handed, and the work I do needs to be done. It isnt something that can be abandoned for a few weeks to take care of something else, *someone* needs to stay with my guys. So long as I work for the company, that person is me. I wish I did something more meaningful, I wish I could make a difference for more than three people. I just want to help.

Anyway, if you can, donate.
 http://www.redcross.com

Dee Dee passed away tonight. I got a call from mom when I got home at 5pm, Dee had been sick the night before and I should come over. I drove right over and Dee was standing in the rain, soaked, shaking uncontrollably. She wouldnt let my mom catch her (last night the vet had put a tube down her nose to give her fluids, and she was understandably skittish about being handled). I slowly got close to her, stepping away each time she did, letting her eventually come to me. It was pitiful, she was shaking so hard, I knew it was bad. She didnt want to walk to the barn, but I eventually got her inside and covered her with a blanket till she was warm. She was still shaking, but not so bad. Levi (mom's horse) was outside and he was just freaking out with her gone. She stumbled and fell, hitting her head against the wall/beam. She struggled but got back up, and I yelled for mom to call the vet and get my brother out here. Rick came out and she fell again, and he helped me get her up. She fell two or three more times after that, bashing her body against the stall, knocking her head. Dad finally came home and said it was colic, and to keep her moving. Well, she couldnt even walk at that point, so we just tried to keep her on her feet. It looked like she was having seizures when she fell. The vet showed up and checked her over and gave her some pain medicine and a tranquilizer. He listened to her heart and apparently her heartbeat was slow and occasionally it would just stop for like 5 seconds at a time, and that was when she would fall over. I asked him to go ahead and end it, just because of the falling and thrashing and how hard it was on her. When she was up she was just shaking and wild eyed. He said he wanted to check something, but to let her lay down. Once she was down, he asked if we wanted to take her to Purdue, but I didnt want to do that. She was an old lady and in a lot of pain, and a two hour ride in a trailer while passing out then trying to get up would just be too much for her. Well, once the decision was made, we tried to get her outside so she could be put down out there, for practical purposes of getting her out of the barn. We couldnt even get her up for that, so there wouldnt have been any way to take her to Purdue. I sat with her awhile, holding her head in my lap and just let her know I loved her and it was okay to go. The vet came in and did his thing, then I just sat there and stroked her head till she was gone. I went out to tell my mom, who was walking Levi to keep him calm. Before, while Dee was falling and getting up and all that, Levi was rearing and bucking outside, but right before I came out to tell mom Dee was gone, he just stopped. I went up and just hugged him and cried, and he stood there and let me love on him. When I went back inside, he started acting up again. Horses know.  I called Tracey, and she said Dee's heart stopping was a rare complication with bad colic, or a bad GI infection. Either way, her chances wouldnt have been good even with immediate surgury. I made the only decision I could have made, considering. So yeah, kind of a bad night all around. She was a good girl and will be greatly missed by me, my family, and especially her main man Levi.
